tool.name: GDVSpectra_Trend

param.name: in_like_nc_file
param.dialogReference: A GDV Trend NetCDF generated by the GDV Likelihood tool. Requires x, y, time dimensions and likelihood ("like") variable.

param.name: in_mask_nc_file
param.displayname: Input GDV Threshold mask NetCDF file
param.dialogReference: A GDV Likelihood Threshold NetCDF generated by the GDV Threshold tool. The threshold areas act as a mask to reduce analysis down to high likelihood vegetation areas. Requires x, y and a threshold variable.

param.name: out_nc_file
param.dialogReference: The folder location and filename of the output NetCDF file containing GDV Trend output.

param.name: in_use_all_years
param.dialogReference:
Combine all annual data within the input GDV likelihood NetCDF when performing trend analysis. A minimum of 4 years is required to perform a trend analysis, with 10 or more recommended.

If not selected, choose a specific range of years to perform the analysis on.

param.name: in_start_year
param.dialogReference: Select a specific start year within the input GDV likelihood NetCDF to start the trend analysis on. This year is inclusive.

param.name: in_end_year
param.dialogReference: Select a specific end year within the input GDV likelihood NetCDF to end the trend analysis on. This year is inclusive.

param.name: in_analysis_type
param.dialogReference:
The trend analysis method to apply to the GDV Likelihood data. Methods include:

- Mann-Kendall Trend: assess if there is a monotonic upward or downward trend over a period of time even if the trend may or may not be linear. The benefit of using MK Test is that a map of trend directions (Tau) as well as statistical significance (p-value) is produced (Mann 1945; Kendall 1975; Gilbert 1987).

- Theil-Sen Slope: also used to determine trends in univariate time series data, with the benefit that it is highly resistant to outliers and is typically considered more robust than the MK Test, though computationally heavier and without a p-value (Gilbert 1987).

param.name: in_mk_pvalue
param.dialogReference:
The significance (p-value) of trend included in the output NetCDF. The lower the value the more significant the trend must be for it to be included in the output.

Set the value to 1 to return all trend values regardless of significance.

param.name: in_mk_direction
param.dialogReference:
The direction of the detected Mann-Kendall trend allowed in the output NetCDF. Options include:

- Both: Both increasing (Tau > 0), decreasing (Tau < 0) and No Trend (Tau = 0) are returned.

- Increasing: Only increasing (Tau > 0) trends are returned.

- Decreasing: Only decreasing(Tau < 0) trends are returned.

Note: this is only used for the Mann-Kendall Trend Test.

param.name: in_add_result_to_map
param.dialogReference: Whether to visualise the results to the currently active map once modelling is complete or not.

tool.summary:
Generates a trend map of GDV Likelihood change over three or more years. This allows users to determine if any long term trends (e.g., vegetation increase, decrease) have occurred within the study area over time. Trend analysis methods offered include the Mann-Kendall Trend Analysis or the generation of Theil-Sen slope.

See citation: Mann 1945; Kendall 1975; Gilbert 1987.
